</div></div></div>
</div></div>
<p>“How To” Tips:</p>
<ul><li>Do a cable chest press from a standing position. Use a dual axis cable machine if available so you can set the machine’s arms to shoulder width.<ul><li>Bend at the waist and press down. No need to “walk the cables out”.</li></ul></li><li>You can do these with one hand or two.</li><li>If two-handed, locate the cable pulleys directly behind your hands so that resistance forms an imaginary straight line from hands, through your forearms and back to the pulleys.</li><li>As with other chest exercises, squeeze your chest muscles throughout so that you don’t turn this into an arm exercise.</li><li>Full range of motion (ROM) is from hands meeting in front of your body with arms fully extended, to upper arms out to the sides and at 90°.<ul><li>Your hands do not need to travel behind your back in order to get a full ROM.</li></ul></li></ul>
<h4><strong>The Cable Crossover</strong></h4>
<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
