<div class="wp-block-stackable-column stk-block-column stk-block-column--v2 stk-column stk-block stk-26bfa5c" data-block-id="26bfa5c"><div class="stk-column-wrapper stk-block-column__content stk-container stk-26bfa5c-container stk-hover-parent"><div class="stk-block-content stk-inner-blocks stk-26bfa5c-inner-blocks">
<figure class="wp-block-table"><table class="has-fixed-layout"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Exercise type</strong></td><td>Isolation</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Target muscles</strong></td><td>Pectoralis major</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Equipment options</strong></td><td>Cable machine</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>
</div></div></div>
</div></div>
<p>“How To” Tips:</p>
<ul><li>Set up underneath the cable pulleys and bend at the waist, pulling the handles downward toward the floor.<ul><li>Do not position yourself in front of the cables. Doing so forces extra effort to keep the core steady and detracts from the focus on the chest.</li></ul></li><li>It’s OK–even preferable–to let your elbows flex a little as you lower the weight. Keeping arms perfectly rigid and straight places unnecessary stress on the biceps tendons.<ul><li>Full ROM is when hands are out to the sides and slightly in front of the chest. You do not need to bring the hands behind your back to get enough stretch in the pecs. Too much stretch risks tendon inflammation or damage.</li></ul></li></ul>
